class Solution {
    public int repeatedStringMatch(String a, String b) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        int count = 0;
        while (sb.length() < b.length()) {
            sb.append(a);
            count++;
        }
        if (sb.toString().contains(b)) return count;
        sb.append(a);
        count++;
        return sb.toString().contains(b) ? count : -1;
    }
}
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n + m)
space complexity: O(n + m)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution efficiently checks the minimum number of times string a needs to be repeated to contain string b as a substring by iteratively appending a to a StringBuilder until its length exceeds that of b, then checking for b's presence. If b is not found after the first check, it appends a once more and checks again, ensuring that b can be a substring if it spans across two repetitions of a. 
